1 Taller1 minería de texto Opiniones de Apps de la Play Store

Se pide:

1.1 Carga de datos

En kaggle podéis encontrar Dos ficheros cvs que contiene información sobre valoraciones de usuarios de apps de la Play Store y de datos sobre cada app. Descargar y documentar estos datos de Kaggle

library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(dplyr)
library(stringr)
metadata_apps=read_csv("googleplaystore.csv")
reviews_apps=read_csv("googleplaystore_user_reviews.csv")

Limpiamos un poco los datos

reviews_apps <- reviews_apps %>% filter(Translated_Review!="nan")

# el dataset contiene muchas apps repetidas, por lo que aplico la función distinc,
# segun la web contiene 9660 apps únicas
metadata_apps <-
  metadata_apps %>%
  distinct(App, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  filter(Category!="1.9")

1.2 Análisis descriptivo básico

Realizar un análisis descriptivo básico de las tablas de opiniones y de las a caracterísiticas de las apps

1.2.1 Solución

tabla1 <- metadata_apps %>% 
  group_by(Category) %>% 
  summarise(count=n(),
            Media_Rating=round(mean(Rating,na.rm=TRUE),2),
            Median_Rating=median(Rating,na.rm=TRUE),
            Sd_Rating=sd(Rating,na.rm=TRUE),
            Max_Rating=max(Rating,na.rm=TRUE),
            Min_Rating=min(Rating,na.rm = TRUE))

Top 10 de Categorias con mas reseñas

top10_cat_reviews <- 
  reviews_apps %>% 
  group_by(App) %>% 
  summarise(reviews_count=n()) %>%
  inner_join(metadata_apps) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(Category) %>% 
  summarise(reviews_cat = sum(reviews_count)) %>%
  arrange(desc(reviews_cat)) %>% 
  top_n(10)

1.3 Análisis de sentimiento

Utilizar los tres diccionarios que hemos visto para análisis de sentimiento y comparar con las calificaciones de los reviews que se dan en kaggle

1.3.1 Separamos las palabras de cada reviews y las reviews para cada App

tidy_reviews <- 
  reviews_apps %>%
  mutate(Review_num = row_number()) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, Translated_Review)

apps_review <- 
  reviews_apps %>% 
  transmute(Review_num = row_number(), App = App)

1.3.2 Usando AFINN

Agregamos una columna con el score de AFINN

reviews_sentiments <- 
  tidy_reviews %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>% 
  mutate(affin_score = score, score = NULL)

head(reviews_sentiments)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7
##   App                Sentiment Sentiment_Polarity Sentiment_Subjectiv~ Review_num word   affin_score
##   <chr>              <chr>                  <dbl>                <dbl>      <int> <chr>        <int>
## 1 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 like             2
## 2 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 best             3
## 3 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 helps            2
## 4 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 best             3
## 5 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                0.25                0.288          2 help             2
## 6 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                0.25                0.288          2 healt~           2

Calculamos la suma de los scores de AFINN de las review

afinn <- 
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(Review_num) %>% 
  summarise(score_sum = sum(affin_score)) %>% 
  inner_join(apps_review)

afinn_all_apps <- 
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(App) %>% 
  summarise(score_sum = sum(affin_score)) %>%
  mutate(method="AFINN")

Gráficamos los scores de las 10 Apps con más reviews

1.3.3 Usando BING

Agregamos una columna con el score de BING

reviews_sentiments <- 
  tidy_reviews %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>% 
  mutate(bing_score = sentiment, sentiment = NULL)

head(reviews_sentiments)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7
##   App               Sentiment Sentiment_Polarity Sentiment_Subjectiv~ Review_num word     bing_score
##   <chr>             <chr>                  <dbl>                <dbl>      <int> <chr>    <chr>     
## 1 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 like     positive  
## 2 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 delicio~ positive  
## 3 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 best     positive  
## 4 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 best     positive  
## 5 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                0.25                0.288          2 healthy  positive  
## 6 10 Best Foods fo~ Positive                0.4                 0.875          3 works    positive

Calculamos la diferencia entre positivos y negativos de las review

bing <-
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(Review_num) %>% 
  count(App, index = row_number(), bing_score) %>%
  spread(bing_score, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(bing_score2 = positive - negative) %>%
  summarise(score_sum = sum(bing_score2)) %>%
  inner_join(apps_review)

bing_all_apps <-
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(App) %>% 
  count(App, index = row_number(), bing_score) %>%
  spread(bing_score, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(bing_score2 = positive - negative) %>%
  summarise(score_sum = sum(bing_score2)) %>%
  mutate(method="BING")

Gráficamos los scores de las 10 Apps con más reviews

1.3.4 Usando NRC

Agregamos una columna con el score de NRC

reviews_sentiments <- 
  tidy_reviews %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc") %>% filter(sentiment %in% c("positive", "negative"))) %>%
  mutate(nrc_score = sentiment, sentiment = NULL)

head(reviews_sentiments)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7
##   App                Sentiment Sentiment_Polarity Sentiment_Subjectiv~ Review_num word     nrc_score
##   <chr>              <chr>                  <dbl>                <dbl>      <int> <chr>    <chr>    
## 1 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 eat      positive 
## 2 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 delicio~ positive 
## 3 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 food     positive 
## 4 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 food     positive 
## 5 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                1                   0.533          1 case     negative 
## 6 10 Best Foods for~ Positive                0.25                0.288          2 healthy  positive

Calculamos la diferencia entre positivos y negativos de las review, similar a bing, solo filtramos los sentimientos de nrc para quedarnos con solo dos

nrc <-
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(Review_num) %>% 
  count(App, index = row_number(), nrc_score) %>%
  spread(nrc_score, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(nrc_score2 = positive - negative) %>%
  summarise(score_sum = sum(nrc_score2)) %>%
  inner_join(apps_review)

nrc_all_apps <-
  reviews_sentiments %>% 
  group_by(App) %>% 
  count(App, index = row_number(), nrc_score) %>%
  spread(nrc_score, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(nrc_score2 = positive - negative) %>%
  summarise(score_sum = sum(nrc_score2)) %>%
  mutate(method="NRC")

Gráficamos los scores de las 10 Apps con más reviews

1.4 Comparando los tres diccionarios

bind_rows(afinn_all_apps, bing_all_apps, nrc_all_apps) %>%
  ggplot(aes(App, score_sum, fill = method)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~method, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y")

Como se puede observar los resultados son similares

1.5 Calcular las tf-idf

Para cada tipo de aplicación calcular las tf-idf y comparar las palabaras más usadas

Haremos un un dataframe tidy con las reviews, la app, y la categoria de la app en una misma row.

app_categories <- 
  metadata_apps %>%
  group_by(Category) %>%
  transmute(App = App)

tidy_rev_cat <-
  tidy_reviews %>%
  inner_join(app_categories)

head(tidy_rev_cat)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7
##   App             Sentiment Sentiment_Polarity Sentiment_Subjecti~ Review_num word    Category      
##   <chr>           <chr>                  <dbl>               <dbl>      <int> <chr>   <chr>         
## 1 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 i       HEALTH_AND_FI~
## 2 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 like    HEALTH_AND_FI~
## 3 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 eat     HEALTH_AND_FI~
## 4 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 delici~ HEALTH_AND_FI~
## 5 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 food    HEALTH_AND_FI~
## 6 10 Best Foods ~ Positive                   1               0.533          1 that's  HEALTH_AND_FI~

Ahora procedemos a remover las stopwords de las reviews

tidy_rev_cat <-
  tidy_rev_cat %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("word" = "word"))

Calcularemos la cantidad total de términos y la frecuencia de cada uno, agrupando por categoria las apps

cat_words <- 
  tidy_rev_cat %>%
  count(Category, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

total_words <- cat_words %>% 
  group_by(Category) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(n))

all_words <- left_join(cat_words, total_words)

head(all_words)

Ahora procedemos a calcular la tf y idf.

tfidf_words <- all_words %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, Category, n) %>%
  arrange(desc(tf_idf))

knitr::kable(tfidf_words %>% filter(Category %in% top10_cat_reviews$Category) %>% top_n(20))
